{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}} {{Infobox non-profit | name = Medical Associates for Research and Communication (MARC) | fullname = Medical Associates for Research and Communication | type = [[International organization]] | founded_date = {{Start date|df=yes|2008}} | founding_location = [[Mumbai]], [[India]] | tax_id = | registration_id = | headquarters = [[Mumbai]], [[India]] | years_active = 2008 - Present | current_members = {{unbulleted list|[[Amita Mukhopadhyay]]|[[Ritam Chowdhury]]|}} | origins = | key_people = | area_served = Worldwide | product = | mission = | focus = advocacy, policy research, outcomes research, health education, translational research | method = | revenue = | endowment = | num_volunteers = | num_employees = | num_members = | leader_title = Director | leader_name = [[Ritam Chowdhury]] [[MBBS]], [[Master of Public Health|MPH]], [[PhD]] | non-profit_slogan = | former name = | homepage = | dissolved = | footnotes = }}
'''M'''edical '''A'''ssociates for '''R'''esearch and '''C'''ommunication '''(MARC)''' is a [[Non-Governmental Organisation]] that works globally with medical students and researchers with little to no background in research. Their primary goal is to help these researchers complete their research work using appropriate scientific methods thereby maintaining high scientific and research standards. Members of MARC were involved in a pilot study that later proved to be a landmark research study that formed the impetus for the creation of a 911 like system in India.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=20467994 | volume=25 | title=Where there are no emergency medical services-prehospital care for the injured in Mumbai, India. | journal=Prehosp Disaster Med | pages=145–51}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://trekmedics.org/resources/global-burden-rti/ |title=Global Burden of Road Traffic Injuries |publisher='Trek Medics International'|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slideshare.net/drvenugopalpp/emergency-medical-services-2020-issues-and-challenges|first=Venugopalan|last= Poovathumparambil |title=Emergency medical services 2020-Issues and Challenges|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref><ref>Das AK, et al. "White Paper on Academic Emergency Medicine in India:INDO-US Joint Working Group (JWG)" web |url=http://www.japi.org/october_2008/u_789.pdf</ref>
==History== MARC was established by [[Ritam Chowdhury]] [[MBBS]], [[Master of Public Health|MPH]], [[PhD]] in December 2008, in [[Mumbai]], [[India]]. Although started in 2008, the foundations of MARC were laid down much earlier in 2005. As per an interview, MARC was established to "''overcome the lack of adequate research training led to improper application of scientific principles. This led to many good research ideas by medical students and researchers being rejected when submitted for review.''" Thus, MARC was formed as an [[NGO]] to help guide medical students and researchers avoid these pitfalls. Members of MARC collaborate widely with many researchers from across the globe.{{fact|date=August 2018}}
==Philosophy== MARC and its members provide a safe environment wherein researchers could voice their concerns. MARC focused on connecting researchers with resources and providing technical or scientific expertise on a pro bono basis. In addition, they conduct health education and community outreach volunteer work in different parts of India. All work done by MARC is pro bono. Collaborators who assist MARC in its activities volunteer their time and thus help in training the next generation of researchers and public health professionals.{{fact|date=August 2018}}
==Members== MARC was founded by [[Ritam Chowdhury]] [[MBBS]], [[Master of Public Health|MPH]], [[PhD]]. [[Ritam Chowdhury]] [[MBBS]], [[Master of Public Health|MPH]], [[PhD]] is also a Visiting Instructor-[[Global Health]] at [[Emory University]] [[Rollins School of Public Health]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://directory.service.emory.edu/?eodentry=P8630997| title= Ritam Chowdhury|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> and statistical consultant at [[Harvard School of Public Health]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/information-technology/2014/11/18/new-staff-addition-ritam-chowdhury/| title = New Staff Addition: Ritam Chowdhury| accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref>
